p.me:
\frac{dH}{dt} 
= 
\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{\partial x}{\partial t}
+
\frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{\partial y}{\partial t}
+
\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}.

statement.p:
Find the Taylor polynomials of degree n approximating
\frac{5}{2-2x}
for x near 0:

static.solution:
f(x)= \sin\!\left(4x\right). Then f(\frac{\pi }{8}) = 1, and
f'(x) = 4\cos\!\left(4x\right) f'(\frac{\pi }{8}) = 0
f''(x) = -16\sin\!\left(4x\right) f'''(\frac{\pi }{8}) = -4^{2}
f'''(x) = -64\cos\!\left(4x\right) f'''(\frac{\pi }{8}) = 0
f''''(x) = 256\sin\!\left(4x\right) f''''(\frac{\pi }{8}) = 4^{4}
So, P_4(x) = 1+\frac{-4^{2}}{2}\!\left(x-\frac{\pi }{8}\right)^{2}+\frac{4^{4}}{24}\!\left(x-\frac{\pi }{8}\right)^{4}.
